entry.title: [reland] tflite/mediapipe/eigen: avoid exposing flags to disable warnings
entry.content:
This patch is exactly the same as the first. It was reverted because

of some code not checking a return value of a function marked as

[[nodiscard]].



eigen's config contains a handful of flags that disable warnings.

tflite was depending on this config via a public_config, which

means any code using tflite was inheriting a bunch of flags that

disable warnings. This is risky, and not something we should do.



This patch splits eigen's config into two. The one that tflite

depends upon via public_config does not disable any warnings. This

means code using tflite no longer disables a bunch of compiler

warnings. As a result of this I needed to add some flags to disable

warnings in other code that was picking up the flags from eigen.

That this code needs to disable warnings is not new, it was masked

by eigen's config.



This also adds -Wno-unused-function to tflite as this was masked

by flags from eigen. Without it the following error is generated:



../../third_party/tflite/src/tensorflow/lite/kernels/internal/optimized/neon_tensor_utils.cc:587:13: error: unused function 'DotprodMatrixBatchFourVectorMultiplyAccumulate' [-Werror,-Wunused-function]

1 error generated.

entry.title: viz: Allow registering a pending HostFrameSinkClient
entry.content:
Currently Viz allows only 1 HostFrameSinkClient to be bound to a

FrameSinkId for the lifetime of this ID. This client maps to the

RenderWidgetHostView for FrameSinkIds associated with a renderer side

compositor.



In order to reuse the compositor for a cross-RenderFrame navigation in

the renderer process, ownership of the FrameSinkId needs to be

transferred between RenderWidgetHostViews.



This change adds an API to register a HostFrameSinkClient in pending

state. This will be used by a speculative RenderWidgetHostView to claim

ownership of the FrameSinkId when the previous RenderWidgetHostView is

destroyed.



The model still allows only 1 HostFrameSinkClient to be registered at

a time. Since this API is only used for same-process cross-RFH

navigations, the old RenderWidgetHostView is guaranteed to be destroyed

before the new RenderWidgetHostView is made visible.

entry.title: [TLSAA][RWS] Fix rSAFor browsertest race condition
entry.content:
It looks like https://crrev.com/c/4150994 accidentally omitted the

expiration from one of the settings that ought to be intentionally-

expired in the ThirdPartyGrantsExpireOverIPC test.



This meant that there was a race between the IPC from the browser

process, and the IPC sent manually by the test; if the browser process

won, then the network service would end up having a non-expired grant,

and the test would pass (because the test's expectation was incorrect,

I think). If the test's IPC won, then the browser process's IPC would

override the network service's grants, and would cause the test to

fail.



Apparently, the inclusion of field trial configs changes the browser's

behaviors enough to affect the outcome of this race, so the test fails

if we run it with field trials enabled.



This CL fixes the missing expiration, and also removes the race

altogether by skipping the update of the browser's

HostContentSettingsMap. It also removes some unnecessary navigations

during test setup.

entry.title: media/gpu/v4l2/V4l2StatefulVD: listen to POLLOUT events on Hana
entry.content:
Hana's v_d_a_tests test cases tend to get stuck because the driver

stops producing events. Reading v4l2 code and [1] playing around

with it, it seems to be because POLLOUT events are not listened to,

and end up jamming some sort of internal queue. Pending a more

thorough investigation, this CL listens to those events on MTK8173

platforms and uses them to try to enqueue more |OUTPUT_queue_|

buffers, somewhat replicating ToT legacy VDA more closely. This

CL doesn't fix all test cases, but the event drying is reduced

considerably.

entry.title: Add page_load_in_process_fuzzer
entry.content:
Overall, this CL splits html_in_process_fuzzer into two fuzzers:

* html_in_process_fuzzer becomes simpler and no longer involves network

navigations

* a new page_load_in_process_fuzzer is able to explore network loads

with custom headers, status codes, etc.



Specifically, html_in_proces_fuzzer now loads pages as simple data:

URIs so there's no call through to the http(s) test server.



The new page_load_in_process_fuzzer is a protobuf-based fuzzer such that

we can later feed it custom protos (as requested by security shepherds,

sort of). It can simulate network loads over HTTP and HTTPS with custom

headers and response codes, as well as simulating custom HTML.

entry.title: mac_toolchain: dont rely on external modules for version parsing
entry.content:
mac_toolchain.py used pkg_resources.parse_version to parse and

ultimately compare version numbers. pkg_resources is deprecated per

https://setuptools.pypa.io/en/latest/pkg_resources.html and

pypa/setuptools a1aeda391a0c (2023-03-05), in setuptools 67.5.0.

pkg_resources.parse_versions implementation has been

packaging.version.Version since pypa/setuptools db23abf7ef84

(2020-12-20), and when available, since pypa/setuptools 9382fa0c05e5

(2014-09-25). However, pkg_resources as installed doest always depend

directly on the packaging.version module, it often depends on a

pkg_resources._vendor.packaging.version snapshot. This means that the

historical presence of pkg_resources doesnt necessarily indicate that

packaging.version will be available by that name.



Rather than relying on an external module for version parsing, just

split the version string on dots. It appears that these version strings

only ever take the form 15.0 (for Xcode 15.0), and dont ever contain

letters or other confounding characters.

entry.title: Fix CHECK crash in DidNavigateFrame.
entry.content:
In RenderFrameHostManager::DidNavigateFrame(), a check was added so that

if a navigation happens to a root node that updates its frame policy, it

expects the frame to be a fenced frame root. However, it is possible for

this to happen to something other than a fenced frame.



The safe browsing intervention system is designed to stop navigations to

pages deemed unsafe. One of the ways it can intervene is by navigating

to an error page after the original page commits (i.e. loading a

post-commit error page). When it does this,

NavigationControllerImpl::LoadPostCommitErrorPage() changes the frame

policy of the page to a fully permissive frame policy.



If a top-level navigation had sandbox flags set beforehand (which can

happen if a subframe in an extension loaded with a chrome-extension://

URL performs a top-level navigation), those sandbox flags will be

cleared out when the FramePolicy is cleared. DidNavigateFrame() will see

this and check to see that the navigated frame tree node is a fenced

frame root, which will fail, causing the browser to crash.



This CL changes that behavior to use the frame tree node's pending frame

policy instead of a new empty frame policy. This will cause the frame

policy to not change while committing the error page, and will allow it

to load without hitting the CHECK.



See https://crbug.com/1487803#c24 for a deeper dive into the issue.

entry.title: [FLEDGE] Rename `manually_aborted` to `aborted_by_script`
entry.content:
There are 3 ways to abort auctions:

1) Navigating away / closing a tab / destroying a frame. Can be done by

user or a script.

2) An AbortSignal.

3) Passing in bad data to a promise or rejecting it.



`manually_aborted` actually covers cases 2) and 3). Since the user

navigating or closing a tab is also something done "manually", arguably

more "manually" than a script running, the new name is a bit better at

indicating this covers cases 2) and 3).



Scripts can cause navigation, but so can the user, so hopefully that's

enough to point away from case 1) a bit.

entry.title: Pass --disable-field-trial-config to tests that need it.
entry.content:
Affected tests already run without the testing config applied,

so this CL makes it explicit.



Context: Browser tests that use ScopedFeatureList and pass

params presently cause the field trial testing config to be

entirely disabled. (details: crbug.com/1491463#c8)

We plan to fix this, but some existing tests rely on this

(fail with the testing config). This CL annotates those

tests explicitly by making them specify the flag for that.



Once all the CLs updating such tests land (sharded via git

cl split), the following CL to make ScopedFeatureList not

disable the testing config can land:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4935093



As many tests are affected, it will be up to their owners

to do any necessary follow up if the tests should be made to

pass with the testing config (per the comments this CL adds).



Note: I did a best effort to have the new flag only apply to the

subset of tests that needed it when it was a single or a small

number of tests that were affected, by introducing subclasses

for the affected tests. In other cases, where lots of tests in

the same file fail, the flag is added to the original test class.



Note: The --disable-field-trial-config flag is passed simply

by name intentionally, to avoid additional complexity from

depending on components/variations and includes to reference

the existing constant for it. The name is unlikely to change and

this way, we need less complex code to add this to the tests.



This CL was uploaded by git cl split.
